The mechanism of CDs-labeled apt1 and QDs labeled apt2 signal tags was confirmed by FTIR spectra (Fig. 3
                        ). For CDs (curve a, Fig. 3A), we can observe one strong peak located at 3450 cm−1, which could be ascribed to O–H stretching vibration. Another two characteristic absorption bands centered at 1600 and 1399 cm−1 were also observed, respectively assigning to the anti-symmetric and symmetric stretching vibration for COO– 
                        [43]. These results indicated the appearance of typical hydrophilic groups like hydroxyl (–OH) and carboxyl (–COOH) on CDs. CDs/apt1 signal tags were produced through covalent conjugation of amino modified apt1 onto carbonylated CDs assisted with EDC/NHS. Compared to that of CDs, an increase absorption for C = O anti-symmetric stretching vibrations and decrease in absorption for C = O symmetric stretching vibrations was observed for CDs/apt1 (curve b, Fig. 3A), indicating the successful covalent attachment of apt1 on CDs through amide bonds [44–46]. When benchmarked against MPA molecules (curve a, Fig. 3B), MPA capped CdZnTe QDs (curve b, Fig. 3B) exhibited the typical absorption bands of carboxyl (–COOH) while the characteristic peaks for -SH group at 2664 and 2571 cm−1 were disappeared. The missing absorption peaks for -SH groups were resulted from their deprotonation upon the newly formed S-Cd or S-Zn bonds [43]. Similar to that of CDs/apt1, the peak located at approximately 1630 cm−1 became stronger while another one at around 1400 cm−1 almost disappeared for QDs/apt2 (curve c, Fig. 3B), demonstrating the same mechanism for the formation of QDs/apt2 between carbonylated CdZnTe QDs and amino modified apt2.
